author: unidentifies
parent_comment: They just kept sending me bills and sending me to collections forever until I had to file bankruptcy because I was unable to complete basic life tasks like getting a job or getting utilities turned on or renting a place to stay because my credit report was so bad. They also tried to prevent me from getting medical care until the bills were paid off. If my kid got sick and I took her to the doctor they would not see her unless I made a payment of $500 or more. More than once she was so sick I had to take her to the ER, and they would send her home saying that she needed to see her GP but her GP wouldn't see her unless we could pay $500-$1000 towards our bill. She almost died. To be clear it wasn't one huge bill, it was a thousand tiny/medium bills. I owed $750k but no bill itself was more than $10k. They would say "just pay us $25 a month!" but if I were to do that with each individual bill it would have been more than I made in a paycheck. tl;dr they annoy you until you give up. Also, don't have a sick kid in America.

comment: I think tripping in Atlantic City would be one of the most horrifying things one could do.
author: themindlessone
parent_comment: A couple of weeks ago my friends and I made a trip to Atlantic City. After a long night of partying, one of my friends and I headed over to the beach to watch the sunrise. As we're sitting on the beach, pretty messed up, an old man approaches us from behind, and we got kind of sketched out, as I believe we were smoking a bowl at the time. But as he approaches in this bright yellow puffy jacket, the man approx 60-75 years old, who resembled a big baby, says "Ah! Enjoying the sun are we!?". My friend and I nervously agree, as he is too close for comfort. He continues walking past us, "Great day to be young!", then turns back, "Great day to be old too!" and kept marching downt he beach. This man filled us both with such joy, we just wanted to walk with him and hug him. We didn't, because we thought we'd freak him out. We were also tripping pretty hard.

parent_comment: Wat? Ad hominem is a fallacy. You're attacking the individual and not the argument itself. Yes, you can attack individuals and show them to be hypocritical, but that's a different case. "Your entire comment is completely wrong because your user name has Kant in it." That's an ad hominem. comment: I use profile switcher addon, I start my browsing firefox, and I fire up my developer firefox from that.
author: texdeveloper
parent_comment: Best way to use a Firefox for Development and for Browsing? I'm developing JS and testing webpages with Firefox. But I don't use it for my daily browsing, because that interferes with my development customizations. Is there a good way to use Firfox for both? Here is a small list of differences between the two instances: - Firefox for Development: Firebug extension, browser.cache.check_doc_frequency=1, custom privacy settings and "clear history when Firefox closes". But, as an example, no Adblock extension. No specific bookmarks needed. - Firefox for Browsing: Other extensions like Adblock (but no Firebug), different lighter custom privacy settings, browser.cache.check_doc_frequency=default. Bookmarks needed. I'm a bit rigid with the customizations of the Firefox Development. To avoid caching side-effects and to start with a clean cache/cookie state, I clean all of it when I close it. Of course, that makes "daily browsing" a bit cumbersome. It may happen that both "instances" are running the same time. Developing on Firefox 1 and looking documentation and searching on Firefox 2. Using different profiles shouldn't therefore work (do they?). Is there a way to accomplish this? Maybe with two different installations or for example Firefox and a differnt clone (but which one which is similar)?

parent_comment: I don't fit in with these people! So, in an effort to be more active I started taking my girls to a park near the older one's preschool. Its a nice park, mixed group, cool. Nobody interacts though and my oldest was heard shouting, "I don't want any of these people to talk to me!" I told her to stop being a diva, and go make friends. So, we live in the Seattle area and rainy days are common. On the rainy days I take them to McDonald's for lunch and play. This is where the title comes in. Some of the moms from the park are there. They have their McCafe and otherwise everything was brought from home. They won't let the kids have fries and turn their nose up at me giving my toddler chicken nuggets. I tried talking to one lady and she gave me the "I don't want to talk to you, but I'm too polite to say so"... I just don't fit in with these people and their scarves and lattes and organic snacks... My children don't subsist on junk, but... Yeah. Just feel out of place. Oh, plus my kids are huge- not fat, i mean top of the growth charts on height and nearly in weight. They are big thick kids and outweigh kids their age and people assume they are older and then think they are dumb for not being more advanced in milestones... They are actually above the curve on milestones. My preschooler is top of her class (for whatever that's worth). They aren't slow, they're huge. I feel like the freak show when I roll in. All giant and middle-class Murican up in here. Its like high school all over again. Why don't you like me pretty mommies??? I need to meet more nerd moms that like beef jerky and rum and let their kids eat fries sometimes.

comment: I think I would have asked for a manager in both instances...
author: dudenell
parent_comment: A Couple Silly Occurrences When Getting My Daily Fix. Both of these stories are relatively short, so I decided to just combine them into one post. They both take place at a Drunkin' Fauxnuts, though two different locations. In my first tale, I stopped in for a coffee on my way to school. I always ordered a large iced, flavored, coffee with cream and sugar. Occasionally, the cashier would inform me that the flavoring was already sweetened since I'd ordered sugar, and I always said that I would still like the added sugar. On this wonderful day, however, our conversation went like so: "Hi! Can I please have a large iced pumpkin coffee with cream and sugar?" "Oh, the pumpkin spice is already sweetened." "That's okay, I'd still like the sugar, please." "But the pumpkin spice is already sweetened." "...I'm aware of that. I still want the sugar, thanks." "No." wtfdidthisbitchjust In my stunned silence, she sort of chuckles to herself and says, "Oh, I understand! Let me get that for you." I decided to give her the benefit of the doubt. She had a pretty thick accent. It was early, I was tired. Perhaps it was all just a misunderstanding. Nope. I watched her make my drink and she didn't add any sugar. I grabbed a couple sugar packets and opened them. I then stopped her for a second and asked to see the coffee before she put on a lid. She looked a little confused, but came over with the coffee. As soon as she set it down, I emptied the sugar packets right into the coffee. "Thanks!" I said brightly, "May I have a lid now, please?" She gave me the lid, I put it on my coffee and left. I seriously had no idea what to even do with that experience. To just bluntly tell me no when you're in the damn service industry is appalling. I used to work in a privately owned coffeehouse, and if a customer wanted me to add 2.5 sugar packets, 1.75 tablespoons of flavoring, and wanted their milk steamed to 140 degrees, allowed to cool to 100, and then steamed again to 170, I would fucking do it. I didn't raise a stink over her or anything, but it really rustled my jimmies for the rest of the morning. Onto Tale #2! Reminder that this is a different location than in Tale #1 I was heading to work and decided to stop in for some coffee and a sandwich with my boyfriend. After I ordered my sandwich, the cashier asked if I wanted to add hashbrowns. I thought for a second and decided that I did want them. The cashier says, "Okay, your total is $15.14 (embellishing the prices here, I don't remember things that specifically)." I give her my card, she swipes it, gives me a receipt and I move down to the pick-up end of the counter with the boyfriend. While waiting, I looked at my receipt and saw that I'd been charged $16.75 rather than the $15.14 I was told. I got the attention of an employee not currently making anything for a customer and told her about the problem. I was calm and everything, I don't get too worked up over less than $2, I just wanted to point out that they shouldn't tell people they're going to be charged one amount and then end up getting charged extra. She came back and our conversation when something like this: "Okay, the problem is that you added hashbrowns. They cost an extra dollar." "Well, that's fine. I'm just saying that I was told I was being charged less than I actually was." "Yes, it's because you ordered the hashbrowns, which cost an extra dollar." "I don't think you're understanding me. I don't mind being charged a dollar more for the hashbrowns. My issue lies specifically with the cashier telling me I would be charged $15.14 and then charging my card $16.75." "Here, why don't I refund the $1 for you." "That's completely unnecessary. I want the hashbrowns, and I'll pay for them. You just can't charge people more after telling them their total." She just apologized, walked off, and came back with the $1 and change from the tax. Of course, I didn't get my hashbrowns, either. :( I know these aren't too bad. I just wanted to share a couple of lighthearted stories from a customer who gets a laugh out of them now.

parent_comment: The SLR-107 comes in a plum option, I believe. It's not the exact same as my SGL, but it is very close. My girlfriend is also waiting for an AKS-74U to happen, so it'll probably happen eventually. As for department funsies, they can only be out of the armory for department use, so I wouldn't be able to just have a range day with it. However, one of the deputies stopped by during handgun training the other day since he is the armorer and function-checked on of the SD's select-fire ARs. I guess the local PD has three select-fire ARs, too, and at one point had an MP5. Not sure if they still do or not, though. The chief almost got a Glock 18, too, but figured the ammo costs weren't worth it. It's actually pretty great being in a town where both the PD and SD are packed full of gun-loving personnel. No one gets hassled for open-carrying here, they generally know what they're talking about, and the ones I've seen shoot have all been pretty dang good shots. I mentioned I had a Saiga-12 to my firearms instructor, so now they want me to bring it to play around with on shotgun day, which is this weekend.

comment: This is a technique that can also aid in starting a lucid dream!
author: cicaro
parent_comment: Another "technique" that has worked for me is to simply lay flat and DON'T MOVE. Then, after a minute or two, I imagine all of my body parts and focus on how heavy they are, how they stay in the same place. This way I percieve it like the limbs are falling asleep one after another. Then I just try not to move. You will definitely feel the urge to move. I have read about this and some people say that the mind tries to look if the body's still awake by making it itch and making it want to move. If you resist that, you fall in a state of the body being asleep, but the mind not (I'm sure it's not really like that, but that's exactly what it feels like). It can be scary just laying there, awake, but also sleeping, but I always fall asleep after 15 minutes at most if I do it like that.

author: totlmstr
parent_comment: LOL@ that Matt Lees video: "Let's just talk about games". Comments section disabled. I tried listening to that video all the way through but it was full of projection, talk about how games suck, women developers hate working on them (nonsense), they need to be created by more "diverse" peoples. From listening to him I began to realize why he hates games. Most people are happy with their vidya, but ever since he took SJW mantle his own perception of the world had become increasingly polarized, warped into black and white - his food tasted bland, he saw imaginary oppression everywhere, and his vidya sucked because it triggered all of his SJW programming for "RAAAAAAPE". Video games didn't suddenly start to suck and then SJWs came in like white knights to save them from their own demise. That's a bullshit narrative. In reality, *gamers who became SJWs suck and now they're trying to spread their own misery into games.* I have a few ex-friends, also gamers, who fell into that camp. And I say "ex-friends" because SJWs are incredibly depressing to be around. They're whiny, entitled and they complain about *everything*. So many of them are just unsuccessful at life, embittered, and are looking for a way to blame everyone else. Many of these so-called "game journalists" are simply using games as a conversation piece, a prop and a punching bag to vent their own personal SJW microaggressions. That have everything to do with their own attitude and little if anything to do with games.

comment: You should have tried being more Caucasian as a kid.
author: randomlurkerspeaks
parent_comment: Beta story #2: I had a blue beta in college named Cornelius. I had him for the first semester of my sophomore year. When the winter holidays rolled around, I had no one to take care of him, so I made plans to look up what I needed to do to take him with me on the flight home. I could find nothing about fish on the airline website, only cats and dogs. I tried calling for information, but came up empty handed. So I did my best, got him a large, clear, unbreakable container and got him prepped for the trip. When I got to the check in desk, the attendant told me I couldn't take him. She even printed out the same pages of the airline rules I'd seen online (which were only regarding what kind of carrier and weight limits wereneeded for cats and dogs, not anything saying other pets were not allowed). She kept telling me I should look around the airport, maybe I could find a family to give him to. (what? Are there not constant recordings playing telling everyone to do exactly the opposite?) It was also pretty late, so there weren't many people in the airport even if that wasn't crazy talk. She refused to let me check in with my fish. So I did the only tong I could do, I left little Cornelius on the counter in a restroom, thinking maybe a janitor would take him home or something, even though I knew a flushing was more likely. I boarded my plane and what do you know? In my row, one seat away from me was another girl from my school with A RED BETA IN HER LAP. I went from being devastated to enraged pretty quickly.
